@lisongxu, in the below equation, setting W_max = cwnd seems superfluous. Also, next time we want to compute K, it will enter the first condition and end up with K = 0.
```
if (cwnd < W_max)
K = cubic_root((W_max - cwnd)/C)
else{
K = 0
W_max = cwnd
}

@goelvidhi RFC8312 was specifically written because there was no accurate CUBIC specification at the time other than the Linux source code (the paper algorithm was outdated.) I think we should try and stick to this for the revision, i.e., document the CUBIC variant that is used in production now, in Linux and other stacks.

That said, *if* there are modifications that we want to propose that would further improve CUBIC beyond what current implementations are doing, that is possible. But I'd like to then see if Linux and other stacks would be open to implementing these improvements -- I wouldn't want to end up with a CUBIC spec that is (again) divergent from what the main stacks do (in some aspects).

As for how to ask, I think an email to the TCPM WG mailing list with a pointer to the respective GitHub issue/PR works best.

Sure, here is the code to generate the cubic columns in tables 1 and 2. 

```
#include<stdio.h>
#include<math.h>

double ww(double C, double RTT, double p){
	double w, tcp;
	w = pow(RTT, 0.75);
	w = w / pow(p, 0.75);
	w = w * pow(C*3.7/1.2, 0.25);

	tcp = 1.2*pow(1.0/p, 0.5);

	if (tcp>w)
		return (int)(tcp+0.5);
	else
		return (int)(w+0.5);
}

int main(){
	double p;
	int i;

	for(i=2;i<=8;i++){
		p = pow(10, -i);
		printf("%g\t", p);
		printf("||%g\t%g\t%g\t||", ww(0.04, 0.1, p), ww(0.4, 0.1, p), ww(4, 0.1, p));
		printf("%g\t%g\t%g\t\n", ww(0.04, 0.01, p), ww(0.4, 0.01, p), ww(4, 0.01, p));
	}

	return 0;
}
```

I made some changes to the code to print out all the columns of Tables 1 and 2.

```
#include<stdio.h>
#include<math.h>

long reno(double p){
    return round(1.2/pow(p, 0.5));
}


long hstcp(double p){
    long cwnd, tcp_friend;

    cwnd = round(0.12/pow(p, 0.835));
    
    tcp_friend = reno(p);

    if (tcp_friend > cwnd)
        return tcp_friend;
    else
        return cwnd;
}

long cubic(double C, double RTT, double p){
    double w;
    long cwnd, tcp_friend;
    
    w = pow(RTT, 0.75);
    w = w / pow(p, 0.75);
    w = w * pow(C*3.7/1.2, 0.25);
    cwnd = round(w);

    tcp_friend = reno(p);

    if (tcp_friend > cwnd)
        return tcp_friend;
    else
        return cwnd;
}

int main(){
    double p;
    int i;


    printf("Table 1\n");
    printf("%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\n", "P", "TCP", "HSTCP", "C=0.04", "C=0.4", "C=4");
    for(i=2;i<=8;i++){
    p = pow(10, -i);
        printf("%.1e\t", p);
        printf("%ld\t%ld\t%ld\t%ld\t%ld\n", reno(p), hstcp(p), cubic(0.04, 0.1, p), cubic(0.4, 0.1, p), cubic(4, 0.1, p));
    }


    printf("Table 2\n");
    printf("%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\t%s\n", "P", "TCP", "HSTCP", "C=0.04", "C=0.4", "C=4");
    for(i=2;i<=8;i++){
        p = pow(10, -i);
        printf("%.1e\t", p);
        printf("%ld\t%ld\t%ld\t%ld\t%ld\n", reno(p), hstcp(p), cubic(0.04, 0.01, p), cubic(0.4, 0.01, p), cubic(4, 0.01, p));
    }

    return 0;
}

```

Thank you all, yes, I agree that this is a very good suggestion.  

What are some common reasons for spurious retransmissions?   

@nealcardwell you mentioned packet ordering, do you know why it is common (now)? because of more wireless/cellular networks?  

@huitema you mentioned ACK compression in your blog (interesting to read!), could you please explain why ACK compression leads to spurious retransmissions? 

Thank you!

@lisongxu, you mentioned: "there are two possible different methods to restore Cubic, depending on whether we restore cwnd or epoch_start". AFAICT it is better to restore both cwnd and epoch_start (to the values they had immediately before the spurious loss detection event). How does that sound?

You also mentioned: "1. restore to the original cwnd just before the spurious loss. For the above example, we restore cwnd back to 100 after detecting the spurious loss. But to do so, we need to shift epoch_start accordingly (i.e., plus the time period between when the spurious loss occurred and when it was detected)." In this case, why would we need to shift epoch_start? Why not restore epoch_start to the value it had before the spurious loss detection event?

My sense would be that the goal for handling spurious retransmissions should be that, as much as possible, the state of the CUBIC algorithm should be restored so that the behavior of the connection would be as if the spurious retransmissions never happened. This is what Reno does in Linux, and it seems to me that this should be doable for CUBIC as well.

